-- tf.h3: `Step 3`: Generate a live site

- Go to `Settings` from the list of the tabs

- Select `Pages` from Table of Content

- Under Branch, click on the drop-down and select `gh-pages`

- Click on `Save`

This will build your GitHub pages and deploy your website.



-- ftd.image:
src: $assets.files.images.gh-page-deployment.png
width.fixed.px: 750
border-radius.px: 10
border-width.px: 1
border-color: $inherited.colors.border
margin-vertical.px: 16


-- tf.markdown:

- Once it's complete, you will find your live site as shown in the following image. To see your business card click on the button `Visit site`.


-- ftd.image:
src: $assets.files.images.live-site.png
width.fixed.px: 750
border-radius.px: 10
border-width.px: 1
border-color: $inherited.colors.border
margin-vertical.px: 16

-- tf.markdown:

In the new tab you can see the default business card.



-- ftd.column:
width: fill-container
margin-vertical.px: 16

-- tf.h3: `Step 4`: Improve the URL accessibility [Optional] 

To quickly view your website, we recommend you to add your URL to the `About` 
section. 


-- ftd.image:
src: $assets.files.images.about-section.png
width.fixed.px: 750
border-radius.px: 10
border-width.px: 1
border-color: $inherited.colors.border
margin-vertical.px: 16

-- tf.markdown:

To do that follow the steps:

- Go back to the tab where GitHub is open

- Open the first tab i.e. `Code`

- click on the `Settings` icon (‚öôÔ∏è)

- Select the checkbox `Use your GitHub Pages website` just below second field 

- Click on `Save`



-- tf.markdown:

Now you can access your website from `About` section.

-- ftd.image:
